Dear [@Shadowmage](https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/profile/138730-shadowmage/), finally started to assemble my SLS/Cislunar Gateway series, and I'm currently stuck at the transposition and docking maneuver where Orion, using a petal adapter, docks with a CG module. Part of the adapter stays behind and though is "transparent" visually doesn't look very nice:

![ZsvrQ0f.png](https://i.imgur.com/ZsvrQ0f.png)

Any idea or suggestion?

Thanks!!
Set the fairing sections to something higher than 1.

After a semi-lengthy EVA to flip all of those, all better now, thanks.

![M6UGrOs.png](https://i.imgur.com/M6UGrOs.png)

Would likely share a lot of functions / have some overlap, with the main difference between them being in the base physical size. The IMU won't fully replace the PPC (as it will only feature diameter scaling), and likely that both will continue to exist. The IMU is more for cases where 'round' won't work -- e.g. for octagonal stuff for landers. (same with the proposed modular decoupler). > > > 22 hours ago, Jimbodiah said: > > > Satellite: > > > > > - 0.625m to 1.875m? > > - **solar panels or rtg** > Stock code does not support optional or disabling of RTGs in a clean fashion. > > - **fixed/folding dish (maybe 2-3 styles depending on range = size)** > Stock code does not support switching of antennas, at least not if they are linked with the animation module. > > - battery > > - tank > > - **optional ion/mp engine (allow 3rd party engines)** > > Can't have optional engines. Either it has an engine, or none. If it has an engine, it would have pre-set stats. Cannot have different types of engines, nor any sort of dynamic/procedural engine. This is not a plugin/code limitation, but is caused by KSPs config file setup and ModuleManager. ModuleManager needs to be able to patch engines, and it cannot unless they have their own modules, which means only a single engine config can be used (I have some ideas to -work around- some of these problems, but would be a giant PITA to do... and I'm really tired of having to work around stock module limitations). > > - sas, reaction wheels, rcs, xmitter, kerbnet, science modules > > - space to add a future science bay? > > > > > > > Service Module: > > - 1.25-5m > > - probe core > > - rcs > > - decoupler > > - **solar panels or fuel cell** > Stock code does not support optional or disabling of fuel cells in a clean fashion that I've seen. > > - battery/tank > > - no engine (use SSTU or 3rd party engines, or even none for LEO tugs etc) > See comments interspersed in quote... As I was saying... most of the stuff that I would actually want to be dynamic/optional... can't be due to stock code limitations (engines, generators, antenna). Which is why these parts haven't moved forward in development in over a year -- there are few compelling reasons to actually make these parts without those features. The generators (fuel cell/rtg) I can possibly work-around by making custom modules, though it would come at a loss in compatibility with many mods (USI, NF, etc), as most other mods' code are hard-coded around the stock modules. The engines are one of the big sticking points -- I really think they should be integrated. Someone will always end up wanting a 'no engine' version. Can't really have it both ways (without a ton of extra work, and lots of duplicate parts in the editor; no thanks to either). What good is a service module that lacks propulsion? The rest of your proposed features are pretty much right on. But without all the dynamic options.... all you are really left with is a fuel tank... which are already available in many shapes and sizes. > > > 22 hours ago, Jimbodiah said: > > > A modular Orion SM would be perfect for a model ![:)](//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_smiley.gif ":)") > This is the other problem I'm running into (on the modeling end of things) -- how would you propose to make a 'modular Orion SM' from a model setup perspective? (e.g. what would be modular about it?) What kind of models would you propose? In order to do it 'right' I always end up needing to create a ton of different models, one for each length \* variant, with little/no ability to share meshes or textures -- which quickly spirals into the hundreds of hours of work, and dozens of MB of added textures. I could perhaps re-use the existing fuel-tank models, but this certainly won't result in any 'Orion' or 'Apollo' styled SM's. I think the 'mandatory' features for them to be a usable part concept (ignoring modeling issues) would include: - Propellant storage (engine + RCS) - Multiple lengths - EC storage - EC generation options (solar/fuel cell/rtg) - Antenna - Probe-core - Reaction wheel - RCS - needs to have adjustable position to balance properly for payload - Main propulsion - Animated/shielded storage compartment -or- integrated and upgrade-able science experiment; possibly only on some variants. Note that 'payload'/'cargo' is not on the list. These aren't *intended* as a one-piece ATV/etc. They are propulsion and service buses. Take a SM that is in the right 'class' (small/med/large) for your payload (supplies/crew module/science package), select length to determine dV, add docking port to the payload if desired, and have a fully functional 2 or 3-part spacecraft. - No diameter scaling - No payload/cargo by default (can use a longer length and use some of the propellant storage for cargo) - ? Maybe optional/integrated adapter selection for the 'top' end, but really shouldn't be needed

Its not a matter of motivation.... its a matter of it will take 10-20 hours to implement the change as I'll need to rewrite nearly the entire module's code.  As I stated previously, the module was *never intended to be allowed to close*.  As such, most of the code reflects that; there is no tracking for animation direction (only a simple counter), no handling for updating of UI names/labels, no capability to reset/reactivate the airstream shield, and about a dozen more things that don't exist that would be needed.

Edit:

Bit of context about how much will need to change in order to implement this 'simple' feature request...

- No support for animation reversal.  Currently it simply counts from 0->config specified deployed value.  When it hits max, it decouples the top node and optionally jettisons panels.
    - Will need to add in a multi-state animation setup.  instead of just 'animating/not-animating', it will need the full 'stopped-at-start', 'animating forward', 'stopped-at-end', 'animating-backwards', multi-state handling.
    - Will need additional UI controls for 'retract'.
    - Airstream shield interaction will need to be adjusted to re-activate when re-closed.
- No support for disabling of auto-decouple on 'deployment'.  The 'top' node will always be decoupled as soon as it is deployed.
    - Will need to add capability to disable the auto-decouple of the top-node.  More GUI controls....
- Need to track if panels are jettisoned or not, and that needs to hook into the retract GUI (can't retract if panels are gone).
    - All 'deployement' related UI options will need to be linked to examine this field; most will need to be disabled if panels are jettisoned.

And that is with only ~5 minutes of looking at the code.  I'm sure it'll be much much worse once I actually start digging into it.  Haven't even thought about any of the other 'features' you guys have discussed.
